{
  "kind": "email",
  "summary_title": "Cover Letter \u2013 Full Stack Engineer at Patrol",
  "variants": [
    {
      "label": "Cover letter",
      "subject": "Full Stack Engineer \u2013 [Your Name]",
      "body": "Hi Sam and Nico,\n\nPatrol's approach to accessibility \u2014 fixing violations at the source code level through agentic AI rather than layering on overlay widgets \u2014 is the right way to solve this problem, and I want to help build it.\n\nI am a full stack engineer with experience building and shipping agentic AI systems end-to-end. At OregonFlora, I own a statewide research platform serving over 150,000 users, where I reduced an ingestion pipeline from 2 hours to 2 minutes through optimized database and caching strategies. I also adopted GitHub Actions and Docker to automate testing and deployment, cutting infrastructure costs by 70%. Working as the sole engineer on a production system taught me how to move fast, make sound architectural decisions, and take full ownership of outcomes \u2014 the kind of environment Patrol runs on.\n\nMy personal projects pushed me deeper into agentic architecture and LLM API integration. I built Papersy, an AI research assistant using RAG, LangChain, OpenAI, and pgvector to surface insights from academic papers through conversational interaction. I also built AuTuber, an agentic AI stage hand that gives streamers real-time control over their broadcasting tools. Both projects required me to design multi-agent LLM workflows, write targeted prompt engineering strategies, and ship reliable, user-facing products from scratch. Refining agentic architecture for correctness and reliability \u2014 exactly what Patrol needs for its accessible code generation pipeline \u2014 is work I have done and want to keep doing.\n\nOn the frontend, I work in React and TypeScript, and I have built UI/UX across PHP, Vue, and SvelteKit projects with relational databases including MySQL and PostgreSQL. I have also maintained a CMS-based web portal for an educational institution, which gave me direct experience with plugin ecosystems and structured admin interfaces \u2014 a foundation I will build on quickly within the Shopify App ecosystem.\n\nI care about what Patrol is doing. Automated screen testing, WCAG compliance, and making the web accessible to people who rely on assistive technologies are problems worth solving well. I am excited by the opportunity to work on a small engineering team where I can contribute to product direction, work directly with customers, and help Patrol scale from where it is today."
    }
  ]
}

